                "name": "Michael G. Coords MD",
                "href": "/profile/Michael-G-Coords-MD"
            },
            "answer_text": "Of course you get paid but when you work out the hourly rate its generally on par with the custodial staff lol. You are mostly cheap, highly qualified labor. I understand not paying you what a fully trained physician may make but as a resident what you get paid only compounds the insult of medical school costs. I know PA\u2019s who make 100k+ a year and most residents I know are at least as qualified as a PA early in residency and more qualified later on The general range of resident salaries is about 35k-75k. I was lucky enough to train at one of the highest paid residencies in NYC and during my last year of residency made about 74k base and then I had moonlighting on top of that. Something to consider during residency is if they allow moonlighting and are there in house opportunities. I had friends making 40k a year in residency and they had to take out loans on top of there medical loans just to get by. Going further and further into debt in a noble profession where we are helping others. I believe a residency should pay you a salary at least on par with what they would pay a PA and have it be a salary you could live off of without having to give up essentials and cut corners in your life just to get by. If you look at the medical system and all its inefficiencies especially in the hospital i could save a TON of money by making changes getting rid of so much admin, people not working hard, paper work, scut work and take those cost savings and pay the residents appropriately ",
