            "author_info": {
                "name": "Jim Lavelle",
                "href": "/profile/Jim-Lavelle-5"
            },
            "answer_text": "Residents get paid, depending on their rank, in the vicinity of $50-$60k per year. Enough to get by on. Probably not enough to start paying off loans. Definitely not as much as they could be making if they got a job straight out of undergrad and did not incur medical school debt. This is one of the reasons why, contrary to the belief of many, doctors don\u2019t make an exorbitant wage. Their wage is commensurate with the amount of training and the job they do, and it can take 10\u201320 years to close the income gap that develops because they don\u2019t have income in medical school, they incur educational debt, they make only enough to live and not enough to save or pay off debt during their residency (and fellowship) which can be anywhere between 3 and 10 years, their debt compounds while they are unable to pay it off, and they come up for air in their 30s with $200k in debt, no assets, and no retirement savings. Don\u2019t even get me started on the whole having kids and saving for college bit. ",
