            },
            "answer_text": "In 1986 I was paid $15,500 per year.  Lowest paid residency in the US.  We all moonlighted at rural ER's.  Our pay went up $1000 per year.  Eventually we were given an extra week of  \"vacation\".    We could not take it without being fired because there were only 3 residents at each level so including interns (who are not really working with us but were in a categorical internship) there were 12 to cover 3 hospitals full time and 6 months of the year one was off at a total joint center.  So extra vacation meant nothing, it  could not be taken as pay.  When I started moonlighting I made $60,000 dollars a year.  Of course I was working quite a number of hours, but the moonlighting kept me afloat.   Now they make $50,000 a year in the surgical sub-specialties.  With inflation they are getting approximately 50% more using inflation CPI values. ",
